# Process Management Commands

## Display Information
- `ps aux` - Display detailed information about all running processes
- `top` - Show real-time system resource usage and processes
- `htop` - Interactive and user-friendly process monitoring (requires installation)
- `pidof firefox` - Get the PID(s) of a running process by name
- `pgrep -l nginx` - Find PIDs of processes matching a name pattern
- `watch -n 2 ps aux` - Run 'ps aux' every 2 seconds
- `uptime` - Show system uptime and load averages
- `vmstat` - Display system performance statistics

## Process Control
- `kill 1234` - Terminate a process by PID
- `killall firefox` - Kill all processes with the given name
- `pkill -f my_script.py` - Kill processes matching a name pattern
- `xkill` - Click a window to terminate its process (requires installation)
- `nice -n 10 my_program` - Start a process with a specific priority
- `renice -n 5 -p 1234` - Change priority of a running process
- `nohup ./script.sh &` - Run a command immune to hangups (keeps running after logout)
- `disown -h %1` - Remove a job from the shell's job table, keeping it running
- `bg %1` - Resume a suspended job in the background
- `fg %1` - Bring a background job to the foreground
- `jobs` - List background jobs

## Process Execution & Debugging
- `strace -p 1234` - Trace system calls of a running process
- `lsof -p 1234` - List open files of a process
- `iotop` - Show disk I/O usage by processes
- `iftop` - Show real-time network bandwidth usage by processes
- `netstat -tulnp` - Show active network connections and listening ports
- `ss -tulnp` - Faster alternative to netstat for network connections

## Process Persistence & Session Management
- `screen -S mysession` - Start a detachable terminal session
- `tmux` - Terminal multiplexer for managing multiple sessions
- `systemctl restart nginx` - Restart a systemd service (e.g., nginx)
- `service apache2 restart` - Restart a service on older init-based systems
- `crontab -e` - Edit scheduled tasks (cron jobs)
- `echo "reboot" | at 03:00` - Schedule a one-time job to run at 03:00
